Tidy tuesday looking at association between phylogeny and popularity

The Tidy Tuesday dataset this week is on New Zealandâs âBird of the Year 2019â so I thought it might be fun to look at how the taxonomy of the birds of NZ correlates with their popularity.

The packages weâll be using this week in addition to the core tidyverse packages are wikitaxa to help convert common names to scientific names, treeio to read the phylogenetic tree into R, ggtree to visualize the phylogeny, and patchwork to combine the tree with so letâs load those and get started.

library(tidyverse)
library(wikitaxa)
library(treeio)
library(ggtree)
library(patchwork)

We can also grab the data from the Tidy Tuesday repo

nz_bird <- readr::read_csv("https://raw.githubusercontent.com/rfordatascience/tidytuesday/master/data/2019/2019-11-19/nz_bird.csv")

The âBird of the Yearâ voting was done in a rather complicated instant runoff system over several weeksm, so if we look at the raw data, we can see that we have dates, hours, and vote ranks because people could vote for up to 5 birds. To simplify this, weâll just look at the total number of votes because that giveâs the same results at least for the top birds that weâre focusing on.

Extract the common names of the top 30 birds

If we look at the dataset, we can see that overall there were 85 different birds in the running for Bird of the Year.

nz_bird %>%
    filter(!is.na(bird_breed)) %>% 
    distinct(bird_breed) %>% 
    nrow()
## [1] 85

For the sake of overcrowding, weâre going to focus on top 30 in terms of total votes

top_birds <- nz_bird %>%
    filter(!is.na(vote_rank) & !is.na(bird_breed)) %>%
    count(bird_breed) %>%
    arrange(desc(n)) %>%
    top_n(30) %>% 
    pull(bird_breed)

Unfortunately, the dataset only provides us with the common names of the birds, while any sort of taxonomic database is going to require (or be more accurate) if we can provide the scientific names.

Use wikitaxa to obtain for scientific names from a birdâs common name

I initially tried to get the scientific names using the comm2sci function from the taxize package, but the results were pretty incomplete and inaccurate, so I next tried the wikitaxa package which provides an easy way to access the WikiSpecies API.

bird_list <- top_birds %>% 
    set_names() %>% 
    map(wikitaxa::wt_wikispecies_search)

Pull results from list

query_results <- map(bird_list, ~pluck(.x, "query", "search"))
query_results[[2]] %>% 
    select(title)
## # A tibble: 3 x 1

missing_birds <- keep(query_results, is.null) %>% names()

Manually fix a few

query_results_fulldf <- query_results %>% 
    map_dfr(compact, .id = "common_name")

bird_names <- query_results_fulldf %>% 
    filter(!title %in% c("Black robin associated gemykibivirus 1",
                         "Steven Chew Kea Foo",
                         "Thyrocopa kea",
                         "Domene tui",
                         "Avian avulavirus 10",
                         "Haplomitrium ovalifolium",
                         "Cerylinae",
                         "Sibine stimulea",
                         "Homaloptera parclitella",
                         "Mohoua")) %>% 
    distinct(common_name, .keep_all = TRUE) %>%
    select(common_name, latin_name = title) %>% 
    mutate(latin_name = str_replace_all(latin_name, 
                                        c("Gemykibivirus" ="Petroica traversi",
                                          "Eudyptula" = "Eudyptula minor",
                                          "Acanthisitta" = "Acanthisitta chloris",
                                          "Ixobrychus" = "Ixobrychus sturmii"
                                          )))
plot_set <- bird_names %>% 
    pull(latin_name)

Manually add scientific name for missing birds because it is only 3. If part of a bigger project, would look into trying to webscrape latin names from wikipedia.

missing_bird_names <- tibble(
    common_name = missing_birds,
    latin_name = c("Charadrius bicinctus", "Apteryx australis", "Eudyptes pachyrhynchus")
)

bird_names_complete <- bind_rows(bird_names, missing_bird_names)

plot_set <- bird_names_complete %>% 
    pull(latin_name)

Save to file and then input to NCBI

Rather than building our own phylogeny from sequence data, weâre going to use the NCBI Common Tree to infer our phylogeny.

write_lines(plot_set, "sci_names.txt")

https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/Taxonomy/CommonTree/wwwcmt.cgi

One species not found

Import tree back into R

raw_tree <- treeio::read.tree("~/Downloads/phyliptree_fix.phy") %>% 
    as_tibble() %>% 
    mutate(label = str_replace_all(label, "_", " ")) %>% 
    left_join(bird_names_complete, by = c("label" = "latin_name")) %>%
    mutate(label = if_else(!is.na(common_name), glue::glue("{common_name} ({label})"),
                           label))

tree <- as.phylo(raw_tree)

ggtree(tree, branch.length = "none") +
    geom_nodelab(geom = "label", size = 3) +
    geom_tiplab() +
    coord_cartesian(clip = 'off') +
    ylim(0.5, 29.5) +
    theme_tree2() +
    theme(plot.margin=margin(6, 250, 6, 6),
          axis.line.x = element_line(color = "transparent"),
          axis.ticks.x = element_line(color = "transparent"),
          axis.text = element_text(color = "transparent"))

Now add vote data for each bird

bar_df <- nz_bird %>%
    filter(!is.na(vote_rank) & !is.na(bird_breed)) %>%
    count(bird_breed) %>%
    arrange(desc(n)) %>%
    top_n(30) %>% 
    left_join(bird_names_complete, by = c("bird_breed" = "common_name")) %>% 
    mutate(label = glue::glue("{bird_breed} ({latin_name})")) %>% 
    select(label, n)

highlight <- bar_df %>% 
    head(3) %>% 
    pull(label)

colors <- c("black", "darkcyan")

p <- ggtree(tree, branch.length = "none") +
    geom_nodelab(geom = "label", size = 3) +
    geom_tiplab(aes(color = label %in% highlight), show.legend = FALSE) +
    scale_color_manual(values = colors) +
    coord_cartesian(clip = 'off') +
    ylim(0.5, 29.5) +
    theme_tree2() +
    theme(plot.margin=margin(6, 250, 6, 6),
          axis.line.x = element_line(color = "transparent"),
          axis.ticks.x = element_line(color = "transparent"),
          axis.text = element_text(color = "transparent"))
p

Make Bar plot

p1 <- p %>% 
    filter(isTip) %>% 
    select(label, y) %>%
    left_join(bar_df) %>%
    mutate(highlight = if_else(n > 8000, "yes", "no")) %>% 
    ggplot(aes(y, n, fill = highlight)) + 
    geom_col(show.legend = FALSE) + 
    scale_fill_manual(values = colors) +
    coord_flip() +
    annotate("text", x = 0.5, y = 12500, label = "# Votes", hjust = 1) +
    xlim(0.5, 29.5) +
    theme_tree2()
p1

p + p1 + plot_annotation(
    title = "Taxonomic relationship and popularity of NZ Birds",
    subtitle = "Top 3 most popular birds are highlighted",
    caption = "Data: NZ Forest and Bird Organization\n Visualization @frau_dr_barber"
    )

ggsave("plot.png", width = 8, height = 6)
